This document describes the firmware build pipeline that integrates a generated Stenotype dictionary header into a Raspberry Pi Pico firmware image — a multi-tree cross-compilation involving CMake, an ARM toolchain, and vendored C++ repositories entirely outside the Rust workspace and not covered by CI or ctx-verify.

The dictionary data (`out/steno_generated_dictionary_data.h`, built by `build-javelin`) must be wired into two files in the vendored `javelin-steno-pico` checkout: its `CMakeLists.txt` (to compile and include `javelin-ext/steno_generated_dictionary.cc`) and `pico_bindings.cc` (to register a `StenoGeneratedDictionary` instance into the runtime dictionary list in `InitJavelinMaster()`). Because `javelin-steno-pico` is vendored and re-synced from upstream, these edits live as a tracked patch (`scripts/javelin_ext_pico.patch`) reapplied by `scripts/apply_javelin_ext_patch.sh` rather than permanent changes to a tree this repo doesn't own. The script SKIPs if the tree isn't cloned, SKIPs "already applied" if the marker is present in `CMakeLists.txt`, and on patch failure FAILs with instructions to regenerate the patch against the freshly synced tree.

The patch's `CMakeLists.txt` hunk adds `javelin-ext/steno_generated_dictionary.cc` to `target_sources` and extends `target_include_directories` with `javelin/` and `../out` (so the `.cc` can include `"str.h"`, `"dictionary/dictionary.h"`, and the generated data header unqualified). The `pico_bindings.cc` hunk registers the dictionary immediately after user-dictionary registration — `StenoDictionaryList::Lookup()` is first-match-by-list-order, so a user dictionary still wins over the generated one, which wins over the bulk map dictionary. A function-local `static` is correct because `StenoGeneratedDictionary`'s constructor is trivial (only sets `maximumOutlineLength` from a constant in the generated header) and has no init-order dependency.

Build order: (1) `cargo run --bin build-javelin` generates the headers; (2) `bash scripts/apply_javelin_ext_patch.sh` wires them in; (3) `bash scripts/apply_javelin_steno_split_patch.sh` works around an unrelated `RESET_COUNT` enum collision between `javelin-steno` and `pico-sdk` by renaming it `SPLIT_RESET_COUNT` in both trees; (4) `mkdir build && cd build && cmake .. -D JAVELIN_BOARD=polyglot && make` in `javelin-steno-pico/` produces the `.uf2` image. Prerequisites (Arm GNU Toolchain ≥12, CMake ≥4, `pico-sdk` and `javelin-steno` cloned, `picotool` available — locally or fetchable from GitHub) are per-machine setup.